WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:12.720
The Enlightenment was a period in the 17th and 18th centuries where thinkers began to question

00:12.720 --> 00:20.740
traditional authority and emphasize reason, individual rights and equality. These ideas would

00:20.740 --> 00:27.400
go on to shape the world as we know it today. Enlightenment thinkers supported the spread

00:27.400 --> 00:34.680
of knowledge. Education was seen as the key to progress. Schools, universities and libraries

00:34.680 --> 00:39.960
were established, making learning accessible to a wider audience.

00:39.960 --> 00:46.120
Denis Diderot and Jean-Dalambierre's encyclopedia became a symbol of this movement, compiling

00:46.120 --> 00:51.100
knowledge on a vast range of topics.

00:51.100 --> 00:59.380
The Enlightenment influenced the arts, encouraging works that valued reason, order and balance.

00:59.380 --> 01:07.580
Neoclassicism became a popular style in art characterized by a return to classical simplicity.

01:07.580 --> 01:16.980
Jacques Louis David's Oath of the Harashi exemplifies this ideal, promoting civic duty and sacrifice.

01:16.980 --> 01:23.260
The discovery flourished during the Enlightenment, thinkers like Antoine Lavoisier revolutionized

01:23.260 --> 01:30.260
chemistry, developing the law of conservation of mass and a new chemical nomenclature.

01:30.260 --> 01:37.180
The Enlightenment's ideals, education, reason, progress continue to shape our world from

01:37.180 --> 01:43.220
scientific advancements to art, culture and beyond.

01:43.220 --> 01:50.580
The legacy of the Enlightenment lives on, influencing how we learn, create and understand the world.

01:50.580 --> 01:56.020
Its impact on society and culture is a testament to the power of knowledge and reason.

